{"id":"nucl-th/9801059","submitter":"Craig Roberts","authors":"P. Maris, C. D. Roberts and S. Schmidt","title":"Chemical potential dependence of pi and rho properties","comments":"12 pages, 3 figures, REVTEX","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev.C57:2821-2825,1998","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevC.57.2821","report-no":"ANL-PHY-8864-TH-97, MPG-VT-UR 120/97","categories":"nucl-th hep-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Using a confining, Dyson-Schwinger equation model of QCD at finite\ntemperature (T) and chemical potential (mu) we study the behaviour of <q-bar\nq>, m_pi, f_pi and the masses of the rho- and phi-mesons. For each of these\nquantities there is a necessary anticorrelation between its response to T and\nits response to mu. (-<q-bar q>) and f_pi decrease with T and increase with mu;\nm_pi is almost insensitive to T and mu until very near the border of the\nconfinement domain; and the mass of the longitudinal component of the vector\nmesons increases with T and decreases with mu. At T=0, the rho-meson mass is\nreduced by approximately 15% at nuclear matter density. These results are a\nconsequence of the necessary momentum-dependence of the dressed-quark\nself-energy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 28 Jan 1998 00:27:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
{"id":"nucl-th/9801060","submitter":"Craig Roberts","authors":"D. Blaschke, H. Grigorian, G. Poghosyan, C. D. Roberts, S. Schmidt","title":"A dynamical, confining model and hot quark stars","comments":"13 pages, 5 figures, epsfig.sty, elsart.sty. Shortened version to\n  appear in Phys. Lett. B, qualitatively unmodified","journal-ref":"Phys.Lett.B450:207-214,1999","doi":"10.1016/S0370-2693(99)00007-6","report-no":"ANL-PHY-8881-TH-98, MPG-VT-UR 121/98","categories":"nucl-th astro-ph hep-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We explore the consequences of an equation of state (EOS) obtained in a\nconfining Dyson-Schwinger equation model of QCD for the structure and stability\nof nonstrange quark stars at finite-T, and compare the results with those\nobtained using a bag-model EOS. Both models support a temperature profile that\nvaries over the star's volume and the consequences of this are model\nindependent. However, in our model the analogue of the bag pressure is\n(T,mu)-dependent, which is not the case in the bag model. This is a significant\nqualitative difference and comparing the results effects a primary goal of\nelucidating the sensitivity of quark star properties to the form of the EOS.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 28 Jan 1998 01:14:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Apr 1999 23:56:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-03-04"}
